```latex
\documentclass[tikz,border=2mm]{standalone}
\usetikzlibrary{shapes.geometric, arrows.meta}

\tikzset{
    block/.style = {rectangle, draw=black, fill=white!20, text width=6em, text centered, rounded corners, minimum height=3em},
    line/.style = {draw=black, thick, ->, >=stealth'}
}

\begin{document}
\begin{tikzpicture}[node distance=2cm]

    % Nodes for AdS/CFT correspondence
    \node (AdSCFT) [block] at (0,2) {Relativistic AdS$_5$/CFT$_4$};

    % Nodes for Non-Relativistic Correspondence
    \node (NonRel) [block, below=of AdSCFT] {New Non-Relativistic Correspondence};

    % Arrows to indicate limits
    \path [line] 
        node[anchor=east] {$\alpha' \to 0$} -- (AdSCFT.west)
        node[anchor=south] {$c \to \infty$} -- (NonRel.south);

    % Commutativity arrow
    \path [line, dashed]
        (AdSCFT.east) -- ++(1,0) -| (NonRel.north);

\end{tikzpicture}
\end{document}
```

This code will produce a simple diagram where:
- The top block labeled "Relativistic AdS$_5$/CFT$_4$" represents the AdS/CFT correspondence.
- The bottom block labeled "New Non-Relativistic Correspondence" represents the new non-relativistic theory.
- Arrows above the blocks indicate the limits: $\alpha' \to 0$ and $c \to \infty$.
- A dashed arrow connects the right edge of the AdS/CFT block to the north edge of the non-relativistic block, symbolizing that these limits commute.

You can compile this LaTeX code using a TeX editor like Overleaf or any other LaTeX distribution to see the resulting diagram.

